  <section>
    <h2>Methodological limits</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Scope differences:</strong> The definition of "fiscal balance" varies by country. Countries that include education and healthcare costs are not comparable to those that exclude them.</li>
      <li><strong>Static vs. dynamic models:</strong> Static models (current tax and benefit flows) and dynamic models (lifetime contributions including descendants) produce substantially different results.</li>
      <li><strong>Population scope:</strong> "All immigrants," "non-Western immigrants," "refugees," and "labour migrants" have fundamentally different fiscal profiles.</li>
      <li><strong>Business cycle sensitivity:</strong> Results vary depending on the economic conditions at the time of measurement.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this data does not show</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Figures across countries cannot be added together. Different methodologies make cross-country arithmetic invalid.</li>
      <li>The fiscal outcome depends heavily on migrant profile (labour migrants vs. refugees / family reunification) and length of stay. The same label "immigrant" can produce opposite results.</li>
      <li>Whether the fiscal balance is positive or negative is not the sole criterion for evaluating immigration policy. Labour shortages, demographic trends, and cultural factors are not captured in fiscal statistics.</li>
      <li>Correlation vs. causation: if fiscal deficits increased during periods of high immigration, this does not mean immigration caused the deficit. Recessions, ageing populations, and other concurrent factors may be at work.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
